## 4.4 Special warnings and precautions for use

The safety and efficacy of {{ drug.name }} in hypertensive crisis has not been established.

Patients with cardiac failure:

Patients with heart failure should be treated with caution. In a long-term, placebo controlled study in patients with severe heart failure ({{ drug.molecular_formula }} class {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and IV) the reported incidence of pulmonary oedema was higher in the {{ drug.name }} treated group than in the placebo group. Calcium channel blockers, including {{ drug.name }}, should be used with caution in patients with congestive heart failure, as they may increase the risk of future cardiovascular events and mortality.

Hepatic impairment:

The half-life of {{ drug.name }} is prolonged and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} values are higher in patients with impaired liver function; dosage recommendations have not been established. {{ drug.name }} should therefore be initiated at the lower end of the dosing range and caution should be used, both on initial treatment and when increasing the dose. Slow dose titration and careful monitoring may be required in patients with severe hepatic impairment.

Elderly:

In the elderly increase of the dosage should take place with care.

Renal impairment:

{{ drug.name }} may be used in such patients at normal doses. Changes in {{ drug.name }} plasma concentrations are not correlated with degree of renal impairment. {{ drug.name }} is not dialyzable.
